  "topic_id": "T03.05",
  "topic_name": "Indices, Exponents and Logarithms",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Indices, exponents and logarithms are fundamental concepts in algebra. An index or exponent indicates how many times a base number is multiplied by itself. The laws of indices help simplify expressions involving powers. Logarithms are the inverse of exponents - if a^x = b, then log_a(b) = x. The common logarithm uses base 10. Understanding these concepts is essential for solving exponential equations and working with large or small numbers in scientific notation.",
    "rules": [
      "a^m × a^n = a^(m+n)",
      "a^m ÷ a^n = a^(m-n)",
      "(a^m)^n = a^(mn)",
      "(ab)^n = a^n × b^n",
      "a^0 = 1 (where a ≠ 0)",
      "a^(-n) = 1/a^n",
      "a^(1/n) = ⁿ√a",
      "log(ab) = log(a) + log(b)",
      "log(a/b) = log(a) - log(b)",
      "log(a^n) = n × log(a)",
      "log₁₀(10) = 1",
      "log₁₀(1) = 0",
      "If log_a(b) = x, then a^x = b"
    ]
  },
